                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d199">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00 Nanking/164: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-05-27T13:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 27, 1927—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>235. Your telegram No. 589 of May 26, noon, and our telegram No. 211 of May 9, 1
                    p.m. Your instructions to consul general at Shanghai approved. With respect to
                    final sentence of first paragraph of your telegram to consul general at
                    Shanghai, keep in mind confidential third paragraph of our telegram No. 211.
                    Consul general should be instructed to inform C. C. Wu that the consul general
                        <pb facs="0330" n="222" xml:id="pg_222"/> is prepared to receive any
                    proposal that Wu may have to make in behalf of General Chiang Kai-shek and to
                    report the same to the American Government for consideration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
